  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is a subtle but profound psychological barrier that arises when individuals from groups historically marginalized in science and technology internalize negative stereotypes about their own abilities. As someone who spent decades immersed in the intellectual world of academia and engineering—both fields where I witnessed firsthand the subtle dynamics of group identity—this phenomenon has always struck me as a complex interplay of self-doubt and systemic inertia. For instance, I recall watching a young woman in my master’s program struggle to articulate her ideas during a group project because she was acutely aware of the stereotype that women aren’t naturally suited for technical work. Her hesitation wasn’t about the task itself but about the fear that her performance might confirm the very stereotype she was trying to defy. This isn’t just about individual anxiety; it’s about a culture that, even in its most well-intentioned efforts, can unintentionally reinforce these barriers. Should we address it? Absolutely. But the solution isn’t a one-size-fits-all policy. It requires a shift in how we frame success in STEM—less about innate talent and more about growth, resilience, and the joy of learning. I’ve seen this play out in my own life through board games and cinema, where the narrative often centers on individual brilliance rather than collaborative problem-solving. In STEM, we must cultivate spaces where everyone feels safe to make mistakes and where the focus is on the process, not the perceived outcome. How? By embedding mentorship early on, creating inclusive environments where diverse voices are not just heard but actively integrated into the problem-solving process. It’s not about erasing stereotypes but about building a culture that recognizes and actively counters their impact. After all, the most transformative ideas often emerge from the intersection of different perspectives, not from a single, dominant narrative.",
